WEBVTT

1
00:00.840 --> 00:04.650
- Welcome back to Understanding
Quantum Information and Computation.

2
00:04.650 --> 00:09.750
My name is John Watrous and I'm the technical director
for IBM Quantum Education.

3
00:09.750 --> 00:15.900
This is the third lesson of the series. In the first two lessons, we talked about the basics
of quantum information.

4
00:15.900 --> 00:20.760
First for single systems in isolation and then for multiple systems.

5
00:20.760 --> 00:28.800
We also discussed standard
basis measurements and unitary operations in both the single and
multiple system settings.

6
00:28.800 --> 00:35.280
In this lesson, we'll introduce
the quantum circuit model, which gives us a standard way to describe quantum computations,

7
00:35.280 --> 00:43.260
and we can also use quantum circuits to describe quantum protocols and other sorts of interactions involving multiple quantum devices.

8
00:43.260 --> 00:49.320
In addition to quantum circuits, we'll also discuss some
important mathematical concepts connected with quantum information,

9
00:49.320 --> 00:56.550
and we'll use them to observe
a few fundamental limitations on quantum information and what we can do with quantum circuits.

10
00:56.550 --> 01:03.865
That'll set us up well for
the lesson following this one where we'll see a few
very important examples and that will conclude the
first unit of the series

11
01:03.865 --> 01:07.680
on the basics of quantum information.

12
01:07.680 --> 01:14.820
Here's an overview of the lesson. We'll start with the quantum circuit model and we'll see how it works.

13
01:14.820 --> 01:21.150
Then we'll talk about the
critically important notion of an inner product, as well as orthonormality and projections,

14
01:21.150 --> 01:29.850
which are connected with inner products. We didn't discuss these things
in the first two lessons, because we really didn't
need to, but now we do.

15
01:29.850 --> 01:34.320
Inner products provide us
with a mathematical tool that we simply could not do without.

16
01:34.320 --> 01:40.230
We just would not get far in understanding quantum information and
computation without inner products.

17
01:40.230 --> 01:46.080
And in the third part of the lesson, we'll take a look at a
few important limitations of quantum information.

18
01:46.080 --> 01:53.550
Ultimately, what we want to do is to explore interesting
things that we can do with quantum information, but in order to do this effectively,

19
01:53.550 --> 01:57.120
we need to be aware of some
things that we can't do.

20
01:57.120 --> 02:03.060
In particular, we'll discuss
the notion of a global phase and why global phases are irrelevant.

21
02:03.060 --> 02:10.500
We'll see a statement of
the no-cloning theorem, which tells us that quantum states can't be copied in general, and we'll see that two quantum states

22
02:10.500 --> 02:18.960
can't be perfectly
discriminated from one another unless they're orthogonal, which is a fundamental
limitation to be aware of.

23
02:18.960 --> 02:24.990
The first topic for the lesson
is the quantum circuit model, which is a model of computation
that provides us with a way

24
02:24.990 --> 02:28.740
to describe quantum computations.

25
02:28.740 --> 02:36.490
The quantum circuit model is
based on a more general notion in computer science of a circuit, and you can define many
different models of computation

26
02:36.490 --> 02:40.170
based on this general notion.

27
02:40.170 --> 02:47.370
The basic idea is that a
circuit is composed of wires which carry information, and gates, which represent operations

28
02:47.370 --> 02:51.570
that are applied to the
information carried by the wires.

29
02:51.570 --> 02:57.900
The term circuit is actually
kind of a strange name to use for this sort of a model
because the word circuit

30
02:57.900 --> 03:01.590
usually refers to a
circular path of some sort.

31
03:01.590 --> 03:07.680
But when we talk about circuits
as models of computation, we're usually talking
about acyclic circuits

32
03:07.680 --> 03:11.160
where circular paths are not allowed.

33
03:11.160 --> 03:19.650
To be more precise, for the
purposes of this series, we're going to demand that
information always flows from left to right in any circuit.

34
03:19.650 --> 03:29.040
So if you prefer, you
can think about circuits as describing sequences of operations where time goes from left to right.

35
03:29.040 --> 03:35.130
Here's an example of a Boolean circuit where the wires carry binary
values, either zero or one,

36
03:35.130 --> 03:39.030
and the gates represent
Boolean logic operations.

37
03:39.030 --> 03:45.210
The wires are represented by lines, and here we have two input
bits labeled X and Y,

38
03:45.210 --> 03:51.960
and if we want to know
what the circuit does on a particular choice of inputs, we propagate the values on
the wires from left to right,

39
03:51.960 --> 03:57.960
depending on the actions
that the gates have on the values that are
carried by the wires.

40
03:57.960 --> 04:07.770
So for instance, we can
take a look at what happens when we start out with the top input wire set to the value one and the bottom input wire
set to the value zero.

41
04:07.770 --> 04:15.060
These two input wires lead
into these two dots right here, which represent fan-out operations, which means that the value is copied

42
04:15.060 --> 04:18.870
so that it can be carried
forward along multiple wires.

43
04:18.870 --> 04:25.710
So if we do this, then these
two wires take the value one, which is the same as this one, and these two wires take the value zero,

44
04:25.710 --> 04:29.520
which is the same as this one.

45
04:29.520 --> 04:36.180
Here we have a NOT gate which
is indicated by the symbol for logical negation, so the
value that comes out is a zero,

46
04:36.180 --> 04:46.380
which is the logical negation of one. And similarly, the value
that comes out of this gate is a one which is the
logical negation of zero.

47
04:46.380 --> 04:53.010
These two gates are AND gates,
this gate is an OR gate, and if we continue on
and propagate the values

48
04:53.010 --> 05:00.690
through the circuit, evaluating
the gates appropriately, then we see that the final value
on this wire here is a one.

49
05:00.690 --> 05:09.480
So the entire circuit describes
a sequence of operations that are composed as the figure suggests, and we end up with a function
from two bits to one bit

50
05:09.480 --> 05:16.380
in this particular case. But in general, there could be any number
of input and output bits.

51
05:16.380 --> 05:23.250
This particular circuit happens to compute the exclusive OR of the two input bits, so the output is a one
if and only if exactly

52
05:23.250 --> 05:31.680
one of the two input bits is set to a one and the other one is set to a zero, but that's not really
important, it's just an example.

53
05:31.680 --> 05:38.190
It's a basic fact about Boolean circuits that any function from any number of bits to any number of bits can be computed

54
05:38.190 --> 05:46.740
by some Boolean circuit, although sometimes you might
need a very large circuit to compute the function
that you're interested in.

55
05:46.740 --> 05:50.250
There are other styles that
are used to describe circuits.

56
05:50.250 --> 05:56.823
For example, this figure
represents exactly the same circuit as we had before, using a style that's perhaps more typical

57
05:56.823 --> 06:03.990
in electrical engineering, where there are conventions for the shapes that represent different gates.

58
06:03.990 --> 06:11.910
We aren't going to use
this particular style, but we will introduce
some symbols of our own for different quantum gates, such as Hadamard gates,
Controlled NOT gates,

59
06:11.910 --> 06:15.300
Toffoli gates, and so on.

60
06:15.300 --> 06:20.640
Just as an aside, here we can see the origin
of the term circuit.

61
06:20.640 --> 06:27.540
In the context of electrical engineering, it's very natural to
think about electricity cycling through a circuit.

62
06:27.540 --> 06:35.010
But in this series we're not
talking about electricity moving through circuits, we're talking about information
moving through circuits.

63
06:35.010 --> 06:44.760
And once again for us, they will always be acyclic, where the information
moves from left to right.

64
06:44.760 --> 06:49.530
Here's a different example of
a different type of circuit called an arithmetic circuit.

65
06:49.530 --> 06:58.410
This time the wires store numbers and the gates represent
arithmetic operations such as addition and multiplication.

66
06:58.410 --> 07:01.410
Here you can see an example
of an arithmetic circuit.

67
07:01.410 --> 07:10.350
It's not important for the sake
of this lesson what it does, it's just an example that's
meant to convey the idea that there are different
notions of circuits.

68
07:10.350 --> 07:17.490
We can also think about
circuits involving randomness, for instance, where the gates represent
probabilistic operations, and if you felt like it,

69
07:17.490 --> 07:25.680
you could probably sit around all day dreaming up new models of computation based on the notion of circuits.

70
07:25.680 --> 07:35.100
In the quantum circuit model,
the wires represent Qubits, and the gates represent both unitary operations and measurements.

71
07:35.100 --> 07:38.880
Here's a very simple example
of a quantum circuit.

72
07:38.880 --> 07:45.420
There's just one Qubit in this circuit, which is represented
by the horizontal line, and the gates, which are
indicated by squares,

73
07:45.420 --> 07:48.870
represent unitary operations that are performed on this Qubit.

74
07:48.870 --> 07:53.700
So there are no measurements
in this particular example.

75
07:53.700 --> 08:00.750
If we want to give the
Qubit a name such as X, we can indicate that in the diagram by putting an X right
here, that's optional.

76
08:00.750 --> 08:10.680
Just like we had for the Boolean circuit from a few moments ago, we can think about this circuit
as representing a sequence of operations where time
goes from left to right.

77
08:10.680 --> 08:17.610
So we start out with X,
we apply the first gate, which is a Hadamard gate
followed by an S gate,

78
08:17.610 --> 08:20.910
then another Hadamard
gate, and finally a T gate.

79
08:20.910 --> 08:26.910
We saw these operations
toward the end of lesson one, and here you can see
their matrix descriptions.

80
08:26.910 --> 08:35.850
So when we perform these
four operations in order, which means first H, then
S, then H again, and then T,

81
08:35.850 --> 08:42.240
the combined operation is given
by this product right here, keeping in mind that the order
essentially gets reversed

82
08:42.240 --> 08:48.810
as we talked about in lesson one. If we perform the matrix multiplication, we get this matrix right here,

83
08:48.810 --> 08:55.980
and so the action of the
circuit on the Qubit X is described by this unitary matrix.

84
08:55.980 --> 09:04.890
Sometimes we'd like to indicate explicitly in a quantum circuit diagram
what input we're feeding in, and we can do that as you see right here.

85
09:04.890 --> 09:07.890
In this case, we're inputting
Ket 0 into the circuit.

86
09:07.890 --> 09:13.830
That's pretty common. We often take Ket 0 to
be the initialized state of a Qubit, but that's not necessary.

87
09:13.830 --> 09:18.060
We could also consider
applying the circuit to a different state.

88
09:18.060 --> 09:26.100
If we choose to, we can also
indicate the output state that we get like this.

89
09:26.100 --> 09:33.660
Here's another example where
this time we have two Qubits named X and Y as you
can see in the diagram.

90
09:33.660 --> 09:40.770
Here we have a Hadamard gate, which is being applied to the Qubit Y, followed by the gate that's indicated by
this symbol right here,

91
09:40.770 --> 09:47.730
which is a Controlled NOT gate. We talked about the
Controlled NOT operation in the previous lesson,

92
09:47.730 --> 09:54.570
and here in this diagram we
can see that the control Qubit is Y, which is indicated by
the small filled in circle,

93
09:54.570 --> 10:01.560
and the target Qubit is X, which is indicated by the large circle with what looks like a plus sign in it.

94
10:01.560 --> 10:05.580
It kind of looks like the
symbol for the exclusive OR so it makes sense.

95
10:05.580 --> 10:11.910
You can imagine that whatever
classical state is stored in Y gets XOR'd onto the Qubit X.

96
10:11.910 --> 10:18.270
And just in the interest of clarity, here's the diagram that
shows the action of this gate on standard basis states,

97
10:18.270 --> 10:22.020
where we assume the A
and B are binary values.

98
10:22.020 --> 10:28.230
For other states, the action is determined
by linearity as always.

99
10:28.230 --> 10:35.760
Now, before we go any further, it will be helpful to
explicitly state a convention that we're going to follow concerning how Qubits are ordered

100
10:35.760 --> 10:39.630
in quantum circuit diagrams like this one.

101
10:39.630 --> 10:46.710
And the convention is that
bottom to top ordering in a quantum circuit diagram is equivalent to left to right ordering

102
10:46.710 --> 10:50.250
as in a tuple or a tensor product.

103
10:50.250 --> 10:57.090
That's a convention we'll
follow in the series and it's also the convention
that's used in Qiskit.

104
10:57.090 --> 11:04.020
So for this particular circuit right here, we're thinking about it as
acting on a pair of Qubits X, Y,

105
11:04.020 --> 11:10.830
X comes first because it's on the bottom, and Y comes last or second in this case, because it's on the top.

106
11:10.830 --> 11:17.820
The way you can think about
this visually, in case it helps, is to imagine rotating
this circuit clockwise so that the inputs are on the top

107
11:17.820 --> 11:22.920
and the outputs are on the bottom, and the ordering of the
Qubits will be correct.

108
11:22.920 --> 11:28.410
Sometimes this ordering trips people up, so just be sure to keep
this convention in mind.

109
11:28.410 --> 11:34.530
So when we think about the action that this circuit describes, what we have first is a
Hadamard gate applied to Y

110
11:34.530 --> 11:41.190
and then a Controlled NOT
gate on the two Qubits with Y being the control
and X being the target.

111
11:41.190 --> 11:47.430
If we wanna write down a unitary matrix that describes the combined
action of these two gates, we can do that.

112
11:47.430 --> 11:51.090
First, we consider the Hadamard gate on Y.

113
11:51.090 --> 11:58.110
We're applying the Hadamard gate to Y and doing nothing to X, which is equivalent to
performing an identity operation on X.

114
11:58.110 --> 12:06.060
And so the action of the Hadamard gate on both Qubits together is
given by the tensor product of the identity matrix and
the matrix representing

115
12:06.060 --> 12:09.210
the Hadamard operation on Y.

116
12:09.210 --> 12:19.500
That looks like this, keeping in mind our
convention that X comes first and Y comes second, so it's
the identity tensored with H.

117
12:19.500 --> 12:26.700
Then we apply the
Controlled NOT operation, which has this matrix
representation, and again, that's consistent with our convention.

118
12:26.700 --> 12:32.070
The second Qubit Y is the control and the first Qubit X is the target.

119
12:32.070 --> 12:37.650
Don't be afraid to pause the video and verify that this makes sense and I'll stop reminding you about that.

120
12:37.650 --> 12:46.740
You can pause these videos, go back and watch parts
as many times as you want, adjust the playback speed if you choose, use them in whatever
way works best for you.

121
12:46.740 --> 12:53.700
Anyway, when we compose the
two operations together, the combined action is described
by this product right here,

122
12:53.700 --> 13:00.630
and these two matrices are
multiplied in this order because the Hadamard is performed first and the Controlled NOT
is performed second,

123
13:00.630 --> 13:08.670
and once again, this is consistent
with what we talked about in lesson one where the ordering
essentially gets reversed.

124
13:08.670 --> 13:12.900
If we perform the matrix multiplication, we get this matrix right here.

125
13:12.900 --> 13:18.900
And we can now read off from this matrix what the circuit does to
standard basis states.

126
13:18.900 --> 13:25.050
If we run the circuit on the input 0, 0, meaning Ket 0 for the first Qubit, Ket 0 for the second Qubit,

127
13:25.050 --> 13:31.740
the result is the Phi+ Bell state, which we can see from the
first column of the matrix.

128
13:31.740 --> 13:38.220
If we feed in 0, 1, we get the Phi- state, one zero gives us the Si+ state,

129
13:38.220 --> 13:43.680
and 1, 1 gives us not Psi-, but -1 X Psi-.

130
13:43.680 --> 13:50.220
The minus sign isn't
really significant here. If you didn't want this to be here, you could perform a swap
operation on the two Qubits

131
13:50.220 --> 13:55.500
to get rid of it and you
wouldn't mess up what happened to the first three standard basis states.

132
13:55.500 --> 13:59.940
But it's really not important
for the sake of this example.

133
13:59.940 --> 14:06.930
So in summary, the circuit has this action right here on standard basis states.

134
14:06.930 --> 14:13.260
When you're thinking about
what a particular circuit does, you don't need to go through
the conversion to matrices and multiply them together,

135
14:13.260 --> 14:21.060
you can also trace through the
action that the circuit has on particular states, and in many cases this will
be the preferred option.

136
14:21.060 --> 14:28.410
In this example, for instance, we can see what the circuit
does to the 0, 0 state by examining the action of the gates.

137
14:28.410 --> 14:36.840
The initial state, which
we've named Pi zero here, just to avoid a name
that would be confusing with the Bell states is 0, 0.

138
14:36.840 --> 14:43.170
We apply the Hadamard gate and the state we get is 0+ which we can expand out like this,

139
14:43.170 --> 14:54.030
and then the Controlled NOT operation takes this state to the Phi+ state, which we can see by thinking
about the action that the Controlled NOT has on
standard basis states,

140
14:54.030 --> 15:00.570
And you can do the same
thing for the other three standard basis states or any
other state for that matter.

141
15:00.570 --> 15:04.410
We can also incorporate classical bits into quantum circuit diagrams.

142
15:04.410 --> 15:08.760
They're indicated by
double lines like you see in this diagram.

143
15:08.760 --> 15:14.910
That is A and B are classical bits and X and Y are Qubits.

144
15:14.910 --> 15:22.590
We have the same two unitary gates as in the previous example, and these symbols right here represent standard basis measurements

145
15:22.590 --> 15:28.920
Specifically after the two
unitary operations are performed, a standard basis measurement
is performed on Y

146
15:28.920 --> 15:37.680
and the result is overwritten
to the classical bit, B, and similarly X is measured and the result is written to the bit A.

147
15:37.680 --> 15:42.540
Here you can see that the Qubits X and Y continue on after they're measured.

148
15:42.540 --> 15:46.770
It's pretty common
though that we don't care all that much about Qubits
after they're measured.

149
15:46.770 --> 15:53.400
Sometimes all we care about
is the measurement result. And in a case like that, we can use the shorthand
style that you see here

150
15:53.400 --> 15:58.650
where measurements have Qubits coming in and classical bits coming out.

151
15:58.650 --> 16:09.150
The understanding here is that
once the Qubits are measured, they're just discarded or ignored and the classical measurement
outcome is carried forward.

152
16:09.150 --> 16:19.290
Now as the series continues, we'll be seeing many
examples of quantum circuits and they'll typically
be much more complicated than the very simple
examples that we just saw.

153
16:19.290 --> 16:24.480
As I mentioned earlier, different symbols are
used for different gates.

154
16:24.480 --> 16:30.540
Single cubic gates are usually
just written as squares with a letter indicating
which operation it is.

155
16:30.540 --> 16:36.450
Sometimes these different
gates are color coded to mean different things, but
we'll ignore that for now.

156
16:36.450 --> 16:39.480
We've already seen the
Controlled NOT gate.

157
16:39.480 --> 16:46.230
Swap gates are denoted
as you see right here, And Toffoli gates and Fredkin gates

158
16:46.230 --> 16:49.410
are denoted as you see right here.

159
16:49.410 --> 16:55.530
Remember that a Toffoli gate is a controlled Controlled NOT gate and a Fredkin gate is
a controlled swap gate.

160
16:55.530 --> 17:04.530
So these symbols are
consistent with the idea that a control Qubit is
indicated by a solid circle with a line connecting it
to the gate it controls.

161
17:04.530 --> 17:12.450
In general, controlled Qubits
don't need to be on the top and these gates don't have
to act on neighboring Qubits, meaning that these gates
can be stretched across

162
17:12.450 --> 17:18.060
other Qubits that they don't act on, and we'll see that
happening in future lessons.

163
17:18.060 --> 17:24.180
One more thing that we often do when using the quantum circuit model is to view arbitrary unitary operations

164
17:24.180 --> 17:29.700
on any number of Qubits
as if they're single gates like you see right here.

165
17:29.700 --> 17:34.530
Just by drawing a rectangle with a label corresponding
to whatever unitary operation it is.

166
17:34.530 --> 17:38.100
In this case it's some
unitary operation U.

167
17:38.100 --> 17:45.000
Of course, we don't know
what U is from this diagram, we have to assume that
U is defined somehow or that we're considering some arbitrary

168
17:45.000 --> 17:53.790
unitary operation U, perhaps. It could be for example that
we just wanna think about U as if it's a subroutine in
the interest of clarity.

169
17:53.790 --> 18:04.770
We also use this notation
that you see right here for a controlled U operation
where the control Qubit is indicated by a solid circle
just like we had before.

170
18:04.770 --> 18:10.770
So that's a brief introduction
to the quantum circuit model. And as I said before, we will see many more
examples of quantum circuits

171
18:10.770 --> 18:13.785
as we continue on in the series.

172
18:13.785 --> 18:21.060
In the next part of the lesson, we're going to take a
look at inner products, orthonormality and projections, which are very important notions

173
18:21.060 --> 18:25.260
in quantum information and computation.

174
18:25.260 --> 18:28.680
We'll start with inner products.

175
18:28.680 --> 18:35.130
Remember that when we
use the direct notation, a Ket is a column vector
and a Bra is a row vector,

176
18:35.130 --> 18:42.930
and specifically the
Bra vector corresponding to a given column vector is the conjugate transpose
of that column vector.

177
18:42.930 --> 18:50.640
So for this vector right here, we obtain the corresponding Bra vector by transposing the vector
as if it's a matrix,

178
18:50.640 --> 18:58.170
which amounts to laying it on its side and then taking the complex conjugate of each of the entries.

179
18:58.170 --> 19:05.520
Now, suppose that we have two Kets with the same number of entries like this.

180
19:05.520 --> 19:13.050
If we form this bracket right here, which simply means that
we take the product of the Bra and the Ket,
as if they're matrices,

181
19:13.050 --> 19:21.540
then we obtain this expression
that you see right here, which is a scaler, or in
other words a complex number.

182
19:21.540 --> 19:26.490
This value is called the inner
product of these two vectors.

183
19:26.490 --> 19:34.110
You can also think about inner products in terms of vectors of the
form that you see right here where the vectors are expressed
as linear combinations

184
19:34.110 --> 19:37.290
of standard basis vectors.

185
19:37.290 --> 19:46.200
The inner product of these vectors is defined in the same way as
before, Bra Psi times Ket Phi which we can express
as a product like this.

186
19:46.200 --> 19:53.310
And if we compute and simplify, we're left with this expression right here for the inner product, which is analogous to what we had before,

187
19:53.310 --> 20:02.340
except this time we're
taking the sum over elements in our classical state set, which is sigma in this particular case.

188
20:02.340 --> 20:08.760
Here's an example that's meant to give you a geometric picture for
how inner products work.

189
20:08.760 --> 20:15.060
Here I've drawn a circle
in a two-dimensional space corresponding to a Qubit, and as long as we restrict our attention

190
20:15.060 --> 20:21.960
to vectors having real number entries, we can draw them as points on this plane.

191
20:21.960 --> 20:25.200
Let's take Phi to be
this vector right here.

192
20:25.200 --> 20:31.230
It's a unit vector, which we can see by
computing the Euclidean norm and that's what this circle represents,

193
20:31.230 --> 20:35.940
it's all of the unit vectors
having real number entries.

194
20:35.940 --> 20:41.670
Let's also say Psi to be
this vector right here, which again is also a unit vector.

195
20:41.670 --> 20:45.930
It's the minus state in fact, but here we're just calling it Psi.

196
20:45.930 --> 20:51.990
If we compute the inner
product of these two vectors, we get one minus the square root of three over two times root two,

197
20:51.990 --> 20:57.330
which happens to be approximately -1/4.

198
20:57.330 --> 21:05.280
The value of this inner product is equal to the cosine of the angle
between the two vectors, which you can see here in the figure.

199
21:05.280 --> 21:11.430
That's something that's
generally true for unit vectors. If we have two unit vectors and they both have real number entries,

200
21:11.430 --> 21:17.790
then the inner product between them is equal to the cosine of
the angle between them.

201
21:17.790 --> 21:25.110
In particular, if the inner
product is equal to zero, like in this example, where we've changed Psi to
be this state right here,

202
21:25.110 --> 21:29.604
then the two vectors must
be at a 90 degree angle to one another.

203
21:29.604 --> 21:37.650
This all generalizes to
vectors in any dimension, by the way, as long as the
entries are real numbers, it's not just for two dimensional vectors.

204
21:37.650 --> 21:46.770
If we have complex number entries, the picture doesn't really
work anymore, but nevertheless, the inner product is every
bit as useful as we will see.

205
21:46.770 --> 21:53.520
The inner product has some
very important properties and we'll take a few moments to observe some of those properties now.

206
21:53.520 --> 21:58.080
First is a connection
between the inner product and the Euclidean norm.

207
21:58.080 --> 22:05.040
If we take the inner product
of any vector with itself, we get the Euclidean norm squared.

208
22:05.040 --> 22:11.490
So we can alternatively say that the Euclidean norm of a vector is equal to the square
root of the inner product

209
22:11.490 --> 22:18.960
of that vector with itself. This isn't a coincidence, this
is a fundamental connection, and here we can see that if we didn't have

210
22:18.960 --> 22:25.800
the complex conjugates in the definition of the inner product, then this formula
wouldn't be true anymore, and we wouldn't have such a useful notion

211
22:25.800 --> 22:31.140
with this fundamental connection
to the Euclidean norm.

212
22:31.140 --> 22:39.930
Next, the inner product
is conjugate symmetric, which means that if we swap
the order of the two arguments, then the value we get for the
inner product gets conjugated.

213
22:39.930 --> 22:46.140
That's expressed by
this equation right here and is quite straightforward to see why this happens for these two expressions

214
22:46.140 --> 22:52.500
for the inner product of the two vectors in the two possible orders.

215
22:52.500 --> 23:00.240
The inner product is linear
in the second argument. Specifically, if we define a vector Phi to be this linear
combination of two vectors,

216
23:00.240 --> 23:08.250
Phi one and Phi two, then the inner product of
any vector Psi with Phi is the same linear combination
of the two inner products,

217
23:08.250 --> 23:12.690
and this follows quite
directly from the fact that matrix multiplication is linear.

218
23:12.690 --> 23:19.680
And we also have that the inner
product is conjugate linear in the first argument, which you can see expressed right here.

219
23:19.680 --> 23:25.800
If Psi is this linear
combination of vectors, then if we take the inner
product of Psi and Phi,

220
23:25.800 --> 23:32.490
then Bra Psi becomes this vector that we see right here where we take the complex
conjugate of beta one and beta two,

221
23:32.490 --> 23:38.790
and so this is the result and that's what's meant
by conjugate linearity.

222
23:38.790 --> 23:44.880
And the last property of the inner product that I wanna mention is
the incredibly useful Cauchy-Schwarz inequality.

223
23:44.880 --> 23:52.140
For any two vectors, Psi and Phi, the absolute value of the inner product can never be larger than the
product of the Euclidean norms

224
23:52.140 --> 24:00.240
of the two vectors. And moreover, the only way that the two
sides of the inequality can be equal is if the two
vectors are linearly dependent,

225
24:00.240 --> 24:04.920
which means that one of them is equal to some scaler times the other.

226
24:04.920 --> 24:12.780
This is in fact one of the
most widely used inequality in all of mathematics and
we use it over and over when we're talking about
quantum information,

227
24:12.780 --> 24:15.840
so it's very good to know about.

228
24:15.840 --> 24:22.050
Next, we'll talk about the
notions of orthogonality and orthonormality which are
connected with inner products

229
24:22.050 --> 24:27.600
and specifically, with
inner products of vectors being equal to zero.

230
24:27.600 --> 24:34.020
To be precise, if we have
two vectors, Psi and Phi, we say that they're orthogonal
if their inner product

231
24:34.020 --> 24:41.670
is equal to zero. And the way that we can think
about orthogonal vectors intuitively is that they're
at right angles to each other,

232
24:41.670 --> 24:45.960
or alternatively, that they're
perpendicular to one another.

233
24:45.960 --> 24:53.430
People sometimes use the term orthogonal to refer to things that have
nothing to do with each other, like saying that one issue
is orthogonal to another,

234
24:53.430 --> 25:02.250
but that's obviously pretty informal and not really meaningful
in a mathematical sense, but the connection is clear if you think about orthogonal
vectors as pointing

235
25:02.250 --> 25:10.020
not in opposite directions, but in completely different directions like north versus west for instance.

236
25:10.020 --> 25:17.070
If we have a set of vectors, we say that the set is an orthogonal set if any two distinct vectors
chosen from that set

237
25:17.070 --> 25:24.660
are necessarily orthogonal to one another, which we can express
as you see right here,

238
25:24.660 --> 25:29.880
An orthonormal set is
simply an orthogonal set of unit vectors.

239
25:29.880 --> 25:36.210
Vectors in orthogonal
sets don't necessarily need to be unit vectors, and in fact you could
even have zero vector

240
25:36.210 --> 25:42.960
being an element of an orthogonal set, but in an orthonormal set, every vector must be a unit vector

241
25:42.960 --> 25:47.700
in addition to the
requirement that the set is an orthogonal set.

242
25:47.700 --> 25:53.880
Given what we know about the relationship between the inner product
and the Euclidean norm, we can express this
condition pretty succinctly

243
25:53.880 --> 25:57.300
as you see right here.

244
25:57.300 --> 26:07.320
And finally, an orthonormal basis is simply an orthonormal
set that forms a basis for whatever vector space
we're talking about.

245
26:07.320 --> 26:13.740
For example, if we take any
classical state set sigma and we think about the set of
all standard basis vectors,

246
26:13.740 --> 26:23.490
we see that this is an orthonormal set and in fact it's an orthonormal basis for the space of all vectors whose entries correspond to
this classical state set sigma.

247
26:23.490 --> 26:28.980
These are all unit vectors and
they're orthogonal in pairs, so it's an orthonormal set.

248
26:28.980 --> 26:34.350
and because it's a basis as well, we have that it's an orthonormal basis.

249
26:34.350 --> 26:43.470
Orthonormal sets are
always linearly independent by the way, so anytime you
have an orthonormal set, it will always be an orthonormal
basis for some subspace,

250
26:43.470 --> 26:49.650
but in this case, we have a basis for the entire space that we're working with.

251
26:49.650 --> 26:54.060
Another example is the set
containing Ket+ and Ket-.

252
26:54.060 --> 26:57.870
These two vectors are orthogonal, their inner product is equal to zero.

253
26:57.870 --> 27:09.150
and they're both unit vectors and they span the
two-dimensional space of vector corresponding to a single Qubit, so they form an orthonormal
basis for that space.

254
27:09.150 --> 27:19.650
Another example is the Bell basis, which is an orthonormal basis for the space of all
four dimensional vectors corresponding to two Qubits.

255
27:19.650 --> 27:29.070
The set containing Ket 0
and Ket+ on the other hand, is not an orthogonal set because the inner product between
these vectors is non-zero.

256
27:29.070 --> 27:38.700
They're both unit vectors and this is a basis for the vector space corresponding to a Qubit, but we don't have orthogonality.

257
27:38.700 --> 27:44.220
Here's a handy fact about orthonormal sets that we'll make use of from time to time.

258
27:44.220 --> 27:52.350
Suppose that we have some
orthonormal set of vectors, specifically, let's suppose
that we have M vectors in this set, Psi one through Psi M,

259
27:52.350 --> 28:00.960
where we're assuming that these vectors are drawn from some N
dimensional vector space, or in other words, each of
the vectors has M entries.

260
28:00.960 --> 28:07.650
As I already mentioned, orthonormal sets are always
linearly independent, so it can't be that M is larger than N,

261
28:07.650 --> 28:12.060
but it could be that M is smaller than N, and that's the case that
we're interested in.

262
28:12.060 --> 28:18.660
And what the fact states is
that if M is smaller than N, then it's always possible
to add additional vectors

263
28:18.660 --> 28:24.180
to the set we started with in order to obtain an
orthonormal basis for our space.

264
28:24.180 --> 28:33.450
To be precise, there must
necessarily exist vectors Psi M+1 up to Psi N so that the entire collection
forms an orthonormal basis.

265
28:33.450 --> 28:44.010
So you can never paint yourself
into a corner, so to speak, by somehow choosing an
orthonormal set of vectors that can't be extended to
form an orthonormal basis.

266
28:44.010 --> 28:51.360
Sometimes you can just look
at the set you start with and figure out how to extend it to form an orthonormal basis, but an alternative that always works

267
28:51.360 --> 28:58.200
is to use a procedure known as the Gram-Schmidt
orthonormalization process to construct these vectors.

268
28:58.200 --> 29:07.050
I won't explain that
procedure in this lesson or in this series because the specifics aren't
really important for us, but of course you can look
it up if you're curious.

269
29:07.050 --> 29:15.480
It's something that can
be performed by a computer in case that's relevant, so
there's no creativity involved, it's just a mechanical procedure.

270
29:15.480 --> 29:25.470
One of the reasons why this
is such a handy fact to have is concerned with a close connection that exists between orthonormal
bases and unitary matrices.

271
29:25.470 --> 29:31.620
In particular, for any square matrix U, the three conditions that you see here are always equivalent,

272
29:31.620 --> 29:35.760
meaning that they're either
all true or they're all false.

273
29:35.760 --> 29:45.660
The first condition says
that U is a unitary matrix, which means that both U dagger times U and U times U dagger are both
equal to the identity matrix.

274
29:45.660 --> 29:55.440
The second condition
says that the rows of U form an orthonormal basis
and the third condition says that the columns of U
form an orthonormal basis.

275
29:55.440 --> 29:58.560
It's actually not too hard
to see why this equivalence is true.

276
29:58.560 --> 30:07.170
Just to keep things simple, let's take a look at a
three by three matrix U as you see right here, where the entries can be any
complex numbers you like.

277
30:07.170 --> 30:13.560
Here on the left hand side I've written U conjugate transposed
just for convenience.

278
30:13.560 --> 30:22.710
If we form three vectors
from the columns of U, which here are named Psi
one, Psi two and Psi three, then if we take the
product of U dagger and U,

279
30:22.710 --> 30:30.360
you can check that each
entry of the product is given by an inner product of vectors as we see right here in this pattern.

280
30:30.360 --> 30:37.290
And now when you think about the condition that U is unitary, which is equivalent to this matrix being equal to the identity matrix,

281
30:37.290 --> 30:42.570
you see that it's equivalent
to the three vectors forming an orthonormal set.

282
30:42.570 --> 30:48.840
The diagonal entries all
have to be equal to one, so these are necessarily unit vectors, and the off diagonal
entries have to be zero,

283
30:48.840 --> 30:52.020
so it's an orthogonal set of vectors.

284
30:52.020 --> 30:58.470
So U being unitary is equivalent to the columns forming an orthonormal set,

285
30:58.470 --> 31:05.070
And that has to be a basis because the number of vectors in the set, which is three in this case, agrees with the dimension of the space

286
31:05.070 --> 31:12.810
that we're working in. You can follow a similar argument for the rows instead of the columns to conclude that U being
unitary is equivalent

287
31:12.810 --> 31:16.170
to the rows farming an orthonormal basis.

288
31:16.170 --> 31:23.910
It doesn't work quite as nicely because we have to make an adjustment to get the complex conjugates
to work in the right way, but the idea is the same.

289
31:23.910 --> 31:31.740
An alternative way to go about it, which is pretty straightforward, is to prove that a matrix is unitary if and only if it's transposed as unitary.

290
31:31.740 --> 31:36.120
And here I do mean to say transpose and not conjugate transpose.

291
31:36.120 --> 31:42.480
It's pretty trivial from the
definition of unitary matrices, that the conjugate transpose
of any unitary matrix is unitary,

292
31:42.480 --> 31:49.500
but it's also the case that the transpose of any unitary matrix is unitary.

293
31:49.500 --> 31:57.210
In any case, we have the
equivalence between these three conditions on any square matrix U, and we can combine this equivalence

294
31:57.210 --> 32:03.570
with the fact about
extending orthonormal sets to form orthonormal bases in order to come up with unitary matrices

295
32:03.570 --> 32:09.750
that do interesting things
or fulfill various needs that we may encounter.

296
32:09.750 --> 32:16.140
Specifically anytime we
have an orthonormal set of M vectors, there will always exist a unitary matrix U

297
32:16.140 --> 32:21.870
whose first M columns are the vectors from that orthonormal set.

298
32:21.870 --> 32:28.130
The remaining columns
can always be filled in so that we obtain a unitary matrix by choosing them so that the columns form

299
32:28.130 --> 32:35.790
an orthonormal basis. This will be a pretty
handy fact for us to have at our disposal.

300
32:35.790 --> 32:42.944
And one more topic for
this section of the lesson is the notion of a projection.

301
32:42.944 --> 32:51.660
A square matrix Pi is
said to be a projection or a projection matrix if the two properties that
are listed here are both true.

302
32:51.660 --> 32:58.470
This is a capital Pi by the way, it's a pretty typical choice for a letter that's used to denote a projection.

303
32:58.470 --> 33:04.980
We often give these typical sorts of names to objects such as matrices just to make them easier to recognize and keep things straight,

304
33:04.980 --> 33:13.440
but you could use whatever name you like. Anyway, the first condition is that Pi is equal to its own conjugate transpose.

305
33:13.440 --> 33:19.500
In general, when we have a matrix that's equal to its own
conjugate transpose, we say that it's a Hermitian matrix.

306
33:19.500 --> 33:24.510
So the first condition can alternatively be stated as Pi is Hermitian.

307
33:24.510 --> 33:31.110
The second condition is
that if we square Pi, meaning that we multiply Pi
to itself, we get Pi again.

308
33:31.110 --> 33:35.520
So squaring Pi doesn't do anything to it.

309
33:35.520 --> 33:44.070
The idea of a projection
intuitively speaking is that it's similar in
spirit to projecting an image onto a screen or dropping
a perpendicular onto a line

310
33:44.070 --> 33:50.250
for instance. When you multiply a
vector by a projection, what you're doing is in some sense

311
33:50.250 --> 33:53.760
leaving a part of it alone
and zeroing out the rest.

312
33:53.760 --> 34:02.250
So if you apply a
projection a second time, it doesn't do anything because
you've already zeroed out the part that the projection zeroes out.

313
34:02.250 --> 34:08.940
An example of a projection
is this matrix right here for any choice of a unit vector Psi.

314
34:08.940 --> 34:13.830
We can check that it satisfies
the required conditions one at a time.

315
34:13.830 --> 34:20.280
For the first one, we compute
the conjugate transpose and this is the conjugate
transpose of a product.

316
34:20.280 --> 34:26.460
And so we can use this formula right here for the conjugate transpose
of a product to help us.

317
34:26.460 --> 34:31.650
What you get is the product
of the conjugate transposes, but the order gets reversed.

318
34:31.650 --> 34:35.010
That happens because of
the transposition part.

319
34:35.010 --> 34:44.190
So if we apply that formula, we obtain this equality right here and we can then simplify to
get back the original matrix.

320
34:44.190 --> 34:47.340
Notice by the way, that we didn't use the fact
that Psi is a unit vector.

321
34:47.340 --> 34:54.180
So in fact, this matrix is
Hermitian for any vector Psi, not just for unit vectors.

322
34:54.180 --> 35:01.080
And for the second one, we square Pi and we obtain
this expression right here and that is equal to the
original matrix this time

323
35:01.080 --> 35:08.310
because Psi is a unit vector, so this inner product
right here is equal to one and that's where the assumption
that Psi is a unit vector

324
35:08.310 --> 35:12.300
comes into play.

325
35:12.300 --> 35:16.050
We can generalize this example and start with an orthonormal set.

326
35:16.050 --> 35:24.990
And if we form this matrix right here, where we sum up the projections corresponding to the individual vectors, then we obtain a projection.

327
35:24.990 --> 35:31.290
Here on the screen, you can see calculations that reveal that and I'll leave it to you to
examine them if you wish.

328
35:31.290 --> 35:38.940
And along similar lines
to the first example, it's the second condition where the orthonormality
of the set gets used.

329
35:38.940 --> 35:46.980
What this projection does if
you multiply it to a vector, is to project that
vector onto the subspace that's spanned by this set of vectors,

330
35:46.980 --> 35:56.130
which in an abstract way is
like dropping a perpendicular to that subspace, and once
you're in that subspace, the projection doesn't do anything.

331
35:56.130 --> 36:03.000
So matrices like this are
examples of projections, and now in fact we've exhausted
all of the possibilities.

332
36:03.000 --> 36:07.920
Every projection matrix takes this form for some choice of an orthonormal set.

333
36:07.920 --> 36:13.590
The zero matrix is a projection, so we do have to make
sure we include that one if we want to get every projection.

334
36:13.590 --> 36:20.070
So just to be clear about this, we are allowing the
possibility that M equals zero and that gives us an empty sum,

335
36:20.070 --> 36:23.250
which we can interpret as the zero matrix.

336
36:23.250 --> 36:32.130
Now that we have the
concept of a projection at our disposal, we can define a more general
class of quantum measurements known as projective measurements.

337
36:32.130 --> 36:38.850
This isn't the most general
notion of a measurement, but it is significantly more general than standard basis measurements

338
36:38.850 --> 36:44.190
and it's going to be very
helpful to incorporate it into our description
of quantum information.

339
36:44.190 --> 36:54.390
A projective measurement is defined by any set of projections
that satisfies the condition that you see right here, which is that the projections
sum to the identity matrix.

340
36:54.390 --> 37:00.420
Here M can be any
positive integer you like so long as these are all projections and this condition is true,

341
37:00.420 --> 37:04.830
the collection defines a
projective measurement.

342
37:04.830 --> 37:10.590
The measurement described
by such a collection works as follows when you
measure any quantum state Psi.

343
37:10.590 --> 37:16.230
First you get an outcome
between one and M, where M is the number of projections.

344
37:16.230 --> 37:22.590
For each possible outcome, K, the probability to get that outcome is the Euclidean norm
squared of the vector you get

345
37:22.590 --> 37:27.870
by multiplying S by Pi
K, the Kth projection.

346
37:27.870 --> 37:31.440
We can also write this
quantity as you see right here.

347
37:31.440 --> 37:39.480
This equality comes from the relationship between the Euclidean
norm and the inner product together with the fact
that Pi K is a projection.

348
37:39.480 --> 37:47.940
From the second form, together with the condition that we have on these projections, we can see right away, by linearity, that our probabilities
will always sum to one,

349
37:47.940 --> 37:52.740
keeping in mind that Psi
has to be a unit vector.

350
37:52.740 --> 38:03.930
And second, assuming that
we get the outcome, K, the state of the system
collapses to the quantum state we get by normalizing whatever
vector we got by projecting.

351
38:03.930 --> 38:09.960
We'll take a look at some
examples in just a moment, but before we do that, let me mention that we don't actually need

352
38:09.960 --> 38:18.030
to number the possible
outcomes from one to M. We can choose whatever names or symbols we want for the outcomes.

353
38:18.030 --> 38:24.060
In particular, if we have a collection of projections that are labeled with symbols
from sum set gamma say,

354
38:24.060 --> 38:30.960
and they satisfy the
same condition as before, which is that they sum
to the identity matrix, then we have a projective measurement

355
38:30.960 --> 38:34.590
that works in exactly
the same way as before.

356
38:34.590 --> 38:46.380
The only only difference here is that we're allowing
the measurement outcomes to be elements of this set gamma as opposed to the integers from one to M.

357
38:46.380 --> 38:55.500
For our first example of
a projective measurement, let's observe that
standard basis measurements are projective measurements.

358
38:55.500 --> 39:04.230
In this case the set of
outcomes of the measurement is the same as the set of classical states of whatever system is being measured.

359
39:04.230 --> 39:11.160
And the set of projections
that describes the measurement is this collection right here, assuming that sigma is
the classical state set

360
39:11.160 --> 39:21.630
of our system. These are all projections
and if we sum them up, we get the identity matrix, so it's a valid projective measurement

361
39:21.630 --> 39:30.420
To see how this works in
a little bit more detail, let's suppose that we
have some arbitrary state that's written in the form
that you see right here.

362
39:30.420 --> 39:38.490
The probability for the
measurement to yield the outcome A, according to the description
from a moment ago, is this value right here,

363
39:38.490 --> 39:45.300
which is equal to the
absolute value squared of the corresponding
entry of the vector Psi, which is what we expect.

364
39:45.300 --> 39:53.520
Conditioned on the outcome being A, the state of the system becomes this, again, according to the
description from a moment ago.

365
39:53.520 --> 39:57.810
If we simplify, we don't
quite get the state we expect, which is Ket A.

366
39:57.810 --> 40:04.410
Instead we get Ket A
multiplied by a scaler, and specifically, this is a scaler having
absolute value equal to one,

367
40:04.410 --> 40:08.340
so it's a complex number
on the unit circle.

368
40:08.340 --> 40:16.080
This is called a global phase and we'll discuss global phases shortly, but for now in short, this
state is equivalent to Ket A.

369
40:16.080 --> 40:23.280
This global phase doesn't
actually have any significance at all and we'll see why
when we get to the discussion of global phases.

370
40:23.280 --> 40:30.030
So (unclear) this issue of global phases, which we'll talk about in just a moment, we see that standard basis measurements

371
40:30.030 --> 40:36.930
are in fact projective measurements. For another example, which is really an extension
of the previous example,

372
40:36.930 --> 40:44.310
if we perform a standard basis
measurement on a system X and we do nothing to a system Y, just like we talked about
in the previous lesson,

373
40:44.310 --> 40:47.550
it's completely equivalent
to measuring the system X, Y.

374
40:47.550 --> 40:51.180
With this projective
measurement right here.

375
40:51.180 --> 40:57.540
We have these projections corresponding to the classical states of X and we're tensoring with the identity on Y

376
40:57.540 --> 41:02.550
which reflects the fact that
we're not doing anything to Y.

377
41:02.550 --> 41:10.590
The description for how
projective measurements work in general tells us
what happens in this example, and I'll leave it to you to
check that this is in fact

378
41:10.590 --> 41:14.970
completely equivalent to what we discussed in the previous lesson.

379
41:14.970 --> 41:25.860
This is all very nice because this projective
measurement description is cleaner in a way and we see that it fits into
this more general picture.

380
41:25.860 --> 41:29.160
Here's one more example of
a projective measurement.

381
41:29.160 --> 41:32.700
This one is a measurement of two Qubits.

382
41:32.700 --> 41:38.970
For this measurement
we have two projections and therefore, two possible
outcomes which are zero and one.

383
41:38.970 --> 41:44.640
The projections are defined
in terms of the Bell states as you see right here.

384
41:44.640 --> 41:52.590
The first projection is
onto the space spanned by the three symmetric Bell states and the second projection is
onto the one dimensional space

385
41:52.590 --> 41:58.860
spanned by the Psi- state, which is the anti-symmetric one, or in other words the
one that gets multiplied

386
41:58.860 --> 42:03.780
by a minus sign if we
perform a swap operation on the two Qubits.

387
42:03.780 --> 42:07.080
We'll see later on in the series why this is an interesting measurement.

388
42:07.080 --> 42:13.800
For now, it's just an example
that connects with something that we've seen before,
which is the Bell basis.

389
42:13.800 --> 42:20.160
One final note on projective measurements is that anytime you have
a projective measurement, you can always implement that measurement

390
42:20.160 --> 42:24.480
using unitary operations and
standard basis measurements.

391
42:24.480 --> 42:32.280
For this particular example of
a measurement, for instance, we can build a quantum circuit that implements the measurement
as you see right here.

392
42:32.280 --> 42:40.500
We imagine that the top
two Qubits are the Qubits that we're measuring with
this projective measurement and what we can do is
introduce a new Qubit

393
42:40.500 --> 42:48.060
that starts off initialized
to the zero state. We perform a Hadamard gate
followed by a Fredkin gate, followed by another Hadamard gate,

394
42:48.060 --> 42:55.620
and if we measure this bottom Qubit using a standard basis measurement, the effect will be exactly the same as if we've measured the top two Qubits

395
42:55.620 --> 42:59.130
with the projective
measurement from this example.

396
42:59.130 --> 43:07.410
We'll get exactly the same probabilities for the two outcomes and the effect that the measurement has on the top two Qubits
will be the same as well.

397
43:07.410 --> 43:14.070
That's not at all obvious. An analysis is required to see that and that analysis isn't shown here.

398
43:14.070 --> 43:21.210
As I've already suggested, we will take a closer look at
this particular measurement in a later lesson and for now
it's just meant as an example.

399
43:21.210 --> 43:29.280
The important point to take away is that something like
this is always possible for any projective measurement, so we don't really gain
any additional capabilities

400
43:29.280 --> 43:35.340
by introducing projective measurements, but it is a very useful concept and we will often speak
of projective measurements

401
43:35.340 --> 43:43.350
as we continue on in the series. The last part of this lesson is on a few important limitations
of quantum information

402
43:43.350 --> 43:47.940
and what we can do with quantum circuits.

403
43:47.940 --> 43:56.040
The first limitation, which maybe isn't so much of a limitation as it is degeneracy, concerns the issue of global phases

404
43:56.040 --> 44:03.810
that I mentioned a short time ago. Here's the definition of what we mean when we refer to a global phase.

405
44:03.810 --> 44:11.400
If we have two quantum
state vectors, Psi and Phi, such that one of them is
equal to the other one multiplied by some complex number alpha,

406
44:11.400 --> 44:19.830
then we say that the states
differ by a global phase or alternatively that they're equivalent up to a global phase.

407
44:19.830 --> 44:26.070
Notice that because quantum state vectors have Euclidean norm equal to one, the only way that this
equation can possibly be true

408
44:26.070 --> 44:33.270
is if the absolute value
of this complex number is equal to one, so alpha
must lie on the unit circle.

409
44:33.270 --> 44:39.690
Let's imagine that we have
two quantum states like this that differ by a global phase and suppose that we measure the state Phi

410
44:39.690 --> 44:42.810
with a standard basis measurement.

411
44:42.810 --> 44:50.850
The probability to get any outcome A is given by this expression right here, and if we substitute
alpha times Psi for Phi,

412
44:50.850 --> 44:56.640
which we can do because we're
assuming that they're equal, we obtain this probability.

413
44:56.640 --> 45:02.700
And if we simplify using the fact that alpha lies in the
complex unit circle, we obtain this probability.

414
45:02.700 --> 45:12.450
Remember that this is the probability that measuring Phi gives the outcome A, but now we see that
this is exactly the same as the probability that measuring
Psi gives the outcome A,

415
45:12.450 --> 45:19.590
so there's absolutely
no difference whatsoever in the probabilities of different outcomes for the two states.

416
45:19.590 --> 45:26.130
A similar argument tells us more generally that for any projective measurement, the probabilities are again identical.

417
45:26.130 --> 45:33.660
So by measuring we can't
tell the difference between two states that
differ by a global phase, even in a statistical sense.

418
45:33.660 --> 45:42.510
Finally, if we apply any unitary
operation to the state Phi, then again by substituting, what we will get is exactly
the same complex number alpha

419
45:42.510 --> 45:48.870
multiplied to whatever we will get by applying the same unitary
operation to the state, Psi.

420
45:48.870 --> 45:53.370
So the two states will still
differ by a global phase.

421
45:53.370 --> 45:59.610
The bottom line is that the two states are completely indistinguishable, so there's really no
difference between them at all

422
45:59.610 --> 46:06.360
in terms of what we could
possibly learn about them from performing unitary
operations and measurements and for this reason,

423
46:06.360 --> 46:12.600
we consider these two
states to be equivalent or if you prefer, that these are just two possibly different

424
46:12.600 --> 46:17.010
vector representations of
the same quantum state.

425
46:17.010 --> 46:25.260
Like I said at the
start of the discussion, it's basically degeneracy
in how quantum states are described by quantum state vectors.

426
46:25.260 --> 46:32.730
In any case, what this means is that we can
simply ignore global phases just like we did effectively when we describe standard
basis measurements

427
46:32.730 --> 46:41.490
as projective measurements. By the way, this degeneracy only happens in the simplified description
of quantum information.

428
46:41.490 --> 46:49.290
When we describe quantum
states using density matrices, as we will do in the
third unit of the series, we will have a unique
matrix representation

429
46:49.290 --> 46:56.310
for every quantum state. The issue of global phases
simply doesn't arise in the general description
of quantum information.

430
46:56.310 --> 47:04.470
It's one more appealing aspect
of the general description of quantum information,
which I keep alluding to, but regardless, global
phases won't bother us

431
47:04.470 --> 47:10.020
because we can just exercise
our freedom to ignore them.

432
47:10.020 --> 47:15.390
Here's a very quick
example just to make sure the notion of a global phase is clear.

433
47:15.390 --> 47:25.740
If we have a minus state, and negative one times a minus state, then these two states
differ by a global phase, and in particular we have
alpha equals negative one.

434
47:25.740 --> 47:31.740
On the other hand, if we have a plus state and a minus state, then we don't have two states
that differ by a global phase.

435
47:31.740 --> 47:36.300
These are orthogonal vectors, so they're linearly independent.

436
47:36.300 --> 47:42.960
To say that two quantum state vectors differ by a global phase
is equivalent to saying that the vectors are linearly dependent,

437
47:42.960 --> 47:46.920
so certainly these vectors
don't differ by a global phase.

438
47:46.920 --> 47:54.600
It's true that the only difference is that this plus sign
turns into this minus sign, but that's what we call a
relative phase difference.

439
47:54.600 --> 48:00.270
That's different from a global phase because we're not
multiplying the entire vector by a complex number.

440
48:00.270 --> 48:07.050
And this is consistent with the fact that we can tell the difference
between these states, in particular, if we
apply a Hadamard operation

441
48:07.050 --> 48:13.470
and then measure, we'll see a zero if the
state was a plus state and a one if the state was a minus state.

442
48:13.470 --> 48:20.340
The next limitation of quantum information that we'll see in this lesson
is the no-cloning theorem.

443
48:20.340 --> 48:27.600
Here's one statement of
the no-cloning theorem and this particular
statement of the theorem is pretty concrete and specific,

444
48:27.600 --> 48:33.720
which will make it easier to talk about. There are other more general ways to formulate the no-cloning theorem,

445
48:33.720 --> 48:37.575
but we'll focus on this one for now.

446
48:37.575 --> 48:42.030
We assume that we have two systems X and Y which have the same classical state set.

447
48:42.030 --> 48:47.700
which consists of the
integer from zero to D-1 where D is at least two.

448
48:47.700 --> 48:54.390
It's not really important what names the classical states have, but by choosing these names it'll help to keep things simple.

449
48:54.390 --> 49:03.150
What's most important
here is that there are at least two different classical
states, so in other words, we're not worrying about the
trivial and uninteresting case

450
49:03.150 --> 49:06.870
where we only have one classical state.

451
49:06.870 --> 49:15.600
What the theorem says is that there's no unitary operation U that we can apply to X, Y so that if we initialize
Y to the zero state,

452
49:15.600 --> 49:21.540
we effectively copy or clone
arbitrary quantum states of X.

453
49:21.540 --> 49:28.950
If we take a look at this
expression right here in isolation, what it says is that for all choices of a quantum state vector Psi of X,

454
49:28.950 --> 49:37.770
applying U to Psi tensored
with the zero state, gives us Psi tensor Psi, or in other words two
independent copies of Psi,

455
49:37.770 --> 49:45.510
so that's what it would mean if we could clone quantum
states and what the theorem says is that this is not possible.

456
49:45.510 --> 49:54.840
You can think about this
in terms of circuits and what the theorem says is
that you'll never be able to come up with a gate or a circuit
that works as you see here.

457
49:54.840 --> 50:02.580
Where one copy of the state Psi comes in along with a collection
of initialized Qubits and two copies of Psi are produced.

458
50:02.580 --> 50:09.870
You can do this for certain
choices of the state Psi, but you can never come up with
a circuit that works this way for every quantum state Psi,

459
50:09.870 --> 50:14.730
and that's what the theorem says.

460
50:14.730 --> 50:22.260
It's quite easy to prove
this theorem, in fact, it essentially boils down to the fact that the transformation we're
looking for isn't linear,

461
50:22.260 --> 50:28.350
but unitary operations are
linear, so it just can't work.

462
50:28.350 --> 50:32.100
Here's an argument in a bit more detail.

463
50:32.100 --> 50:40.050
Suppose that we have a unitary operation U that clones the standard basis
states, Ket 0 and Ket one.

464
50:40.050 --> 50:47.790
We know that the classical
states zero and one must belong to our classical state set because D is at least two.

465
50:47.790 --> 50:54.390
But this means by linearity
that if X is in a plus state, which we can write like this,

466
50:54.390 --> 50:59.490
then the result is this linear combination of these two states right here.

467
50:59.490 --> 51:06.030
However, that's not the right behavior. The requirement on U is that
U cloned is a plus state,

468
51:06.030 --> 51:10.590
which means that we have to
have this equation right here being satisfied.

469
51:10.590 --> 51:18.420
These two states aren't the
same and so it doesn't work and that's all there is to it.

470
51:18.420 --> 51:22.530
Just a few additional remarks
about the no-cloning theorem.

471
51:22.530 --> 51:26.850
First, this statement of the
no-cloning theorem is absolute in some sense.

472
51:26.850 --> 51:33.150
It simply says that a unitary operation U that works exactly like
this doesn't exist.

473
51:33.150 --> 51:40.200
So you might ask whether
or not there exists unitary operation U that
does this approximately with respect to some way of describing

474
51:40.200 --> 51:46.200
an approximation to the statement. There are different
notions of approximation that one might be interested in

475
51:46.200 --> 51:52.320
and we'll see a couple
of them in the third unit of the series, but for these different
notions of approximation,

476
51:52.320 --> 52:00.900
there are quantitative statements
of the no-cloning theorem that put strong limits on how well you can approximately clone.

477
52:00.900 --> 52:07.830
A second remark is that copying or cloning standard basis states most
certainly is possible.

478
52:07.830 --> 52:13.770
For example, a Controlled NOT gate copies the standard basis states of a Qubit.

479
52:13.770 --> 52:21.000
This doesn't contradict
the no-cloning theorem. The point is that cloning in the sense of the no-cloning theorem requires
that this works not only

480
52:21.000 --> 52:24.450
for standard basis states
but for all states.

481
52:24.450 --> 52:29.550
A Controlled NOT gate
certainly doesn't clone a plus state for instance.

482
52:29.550 --> 52:35.790
And finally, it is worth pointing out that there's also a no-cloning theorem for
probabilistic states.

483
52:35.790 --> 52:39.870
It's just not something
that people talk about or care about.

484
52:39.870 --> 52:47.520
If somebody randomly
chooses a bit, for instance, for some arbitrary way of
assigning probabilities to the two values and
then hands you that bit,

485
52:47.520 --> 52:52.440
of course there's no way for you to obtain two independent samples
of that random bit.

486
52:52.440 --> 52:55.500
You just don't know what
the probabilities are.

487
52:55.500 --> 53:03.390
You can copy the bit just like a Controlled NOT
copies standard basis states, but that's not the same thing as cloning the probabilistic state.

488
53:03.390 --> 53:08.970
You just don't have enough
information to do that. Whatever random bit you were given doesn't tell you what
the probabilities were.

489
53:08.970 --> 53:12.000
It's just a bit.

490
53:12.000 --> 53:17.610
The impossibility of cloning
a probabilistic state follows from exactly the same reasoning as in the quantum setting.

491
53:17.610 --> 53:25.980
Cloning is a non-linear process, whereas probabilistic operations, just like unitary operations, are linear.

492
53:25.980 --> 53:33.120
Anyway, it's not surprising
that we can't clone on a probabilistic state and
somehow it's not as interesting as the fact that we can't
clone a quantum state,

493
53:33.120 --> 53:38.250
but the point is simply to observe that this is not a uniquely
quantum phenomenon.

494
53:38.250 --> 53:44.850
The final limitation
of quantum information that we'll discuss in this lesson is that it's not possible
to perfectly discriminate

495
53:44.850 --> 53:48.570
two quantum states that aren't orthogonal.

496
53:48.570 --> 53:55.950
Another way of saying this
is that if two quantum states can be perfectly discriminated, then they have to be orthogonal.

497
53:55.950 --> 54:03.600
What we mean when we refer
to a perfect discrimination of two quantum states, Psi and Phi, is that there's some
way to tell them apart

498
54:03.600 --> 54:06.750
without any chance of error.

499
54:06.750 --> 54:13.320
In terms of the quantum circuit model, we can express this as you
see here on the screen.

500
54:13.320 --> 54:20.130
We have some unitary operation U, which could be implemented
as a quantum circuit or we could just think about U abstractly

501
54:20.130 --> 54:26.670
as a unitary operation
and force input U takes either the state Psi or the state Phi

502
54:26.670 --> 54:34.500
along with a bunch of initialized Qubits, which you can think of as workspace Qubits that somehow assist in this
process of discrimination.

503
54:34.500 --> 54:42.510
After U as applied, the top Qubit is measured with respect to a standard basis measurement and here's the perfect
discrimination part.

504
54:42.510 --> 54:49.500
If the input state was Psi, then the measurement must
give the outcome zero, 100% of the time, and if
the input state was Phi,

505
54:49.500 --> 54:54.900
then the measurement must
give the outcome one, again with 100% chance.

506
54:54.900 --> 54:59.160
It's not important what the
states of these other Qubits are after U was applied.

507
54:59.160 --> 55:07.710
All that matters is this one bit that we get from the measurement because that's the bit that's telling us which of the two states we started with.

508
55:07.710 --> 55:15.210
For some choices of states, Psi and Phi, it will be possible to perform a perfect discrimination like
this and for others it won't.

509
55:15.210 --> 55:21.417
And what we'll observe is that
if it is possible to do this, then Psi and Phi have
to be orthogonal states

510
55:21.417 --> 55:28.530
and that means if Phi and
Psi are not orthogonal, you can't perfectly discriminate them.

511
55:28.530 --> 55:33.900
So let's see why a perfect discrimination implies orthogonality.

512
55:33.900 --> 55:39.630
We'll start by writing down two equations that express what these
two diagrams express.

513
55:39.630 --> 55:46.380
If we think about the quantum state, we get after applying U to a
bunch of initialized Qubits together with the state Psi,

514
55:46.380 --> 55:54.180
we see that it has to
have this form right here, where Pi zero is some quantum state vector representing the state
of all of these Qubits

515
55:54.180 --> 56:01.950
except for the top one. We don't have any information
about this quantum state, Pi zero, it could be anything,

516
56:01.950 --> 56:11.580
but we know that the entire
state has to look like this because that's the only
way that the measurement is guaranteed to give the
outcome zero, 100% of the time.

517
56:11.580 --> 56:14.970
And we have an analogous
equation for the second one.

518
56:14.970 --> 56:21.120
This time the top Qubit
has to be in the one state and similar to Pi zero, the
state Pi one could be anything.

519
56:21.120 --> 56:28.350
And in addition to having
no information about Pi one, we also don't know anything
about the relationship between Pi zero and Pi one.

520
56:28.350 --> 56:33.540
For all we know, these are just two
arbitrary quantum states.

521
56:33.540 --> 56:41.040
What we can do next is
to multiply both sides of these equations on
both sides by U dagger, meaning the conjugate transpose of U.

522
56:41.040 --> 56:45.870
And if we do that, we get the two equations
that you see right here.

523
56:45.870 --> 56:49.200
We're using the fact that U dagger times U is the identity matrix.

524
56:49.200 --> 56:55.290
So that's why we don't see U or U dagger on the left hand side of either equation.

525
56:55.290 --> 57:00.150
And now we can consider the inner product between Psi and Phi.

526
57:00.150 --> 57:06.300
It's the same as the inner
product of Psi and Phi multiplied to the inner
product of the L zero state with itself

527
57:06.300 --> 57:12.720
because the inner product of
any state with itself is one and that includes the L zero state.

528
57:12.720 --> 57:18.930
And now if we look at our two equations, we see that this expression here is equal to the inner product of the vectors

529
57:18.930 --> 57:26.430
represented by the two equations. And in particular it's the inner product between the left hand
sides of these equations.

530
57:26.430 --> 57:33.810
So we can equally well
express this inner product as the inner product of the vectors represented by the right hand
sides of these equations,

531
57:33.810 --> 57:37.830
because the left hand side is
equal to the right hand side for both equations.

532
57:37.830 --> 57:44.730
So we get this expression right here, which is the inner product
of the two right hand sides of the equations or equivalently,

533
57:44.730 --> 57:48.300
it's the conjugate transpose of the first multiplied to the second.

534
57:48.300 --> 57:53.700
U times U dagger is equal
to the identity matrix, because U is unitary and so it goes away.

535
57:53.700 --> 57:59.250
And we can simplify just a little bit to get the product of
these inner products.

536
57:59.250 --> 58:05.400
Now remember that we don't know anything about the relationship
between Pi zero and Pi one, so we don't know what
their inner product is.

537
58:05.400 --> 58:13.410
That's a mystery to us. But whatever it is, we're multiplying it to the inner product of Ket 0 and Ket one, which is zero.

538
58:13.410 --> 58:21.060
So the end result is that
we obtain the value zero, but that's what we wanted to show, the inner product between
Psi and Phi is equal to zero.

539
58:21.060 --> 58:24.090
So the two states are orthogonal.

540
58:24.090 --> 58:30.270
So don't bother trying
to perfectly discriminate two non-orthogonal quantum
states, you just can't do it.

541
58:30.270 --> 58:36.630
There is a converse to the
statement that we just proved, which is that orthogonal quantum states always can be perfectly discriminated,

542
58:36.630 --> 58:42.360
and this is not too hard to
see if we make use of a fact that I mentioned earlier in the lesson.

543
58:42.360 --> 58:49.230
Specifically if Psi and
Phi are orthogonal states, then one thing that we can do is to choose any unitary matrix U

544
58:49.230 --> 58:52.980
whose first two columns
are the two states.

545
58:52.980 --> 59:00.120
We know that it's always
possible to do this and it doesn't matter
for the sake of this task exactly how this unitary matrix is chosen.

546
59:00.120 --> 59:04.380
All that's important is that these are the first two columns.

547
59:04.380 --> 59:12.270
We don't need any additional Qubits. If we simply apply U to
the two possible states, then we'll get these
two possible outcomes.

548
59:12.270 --> 59:18.270
And if we measure the top most Qubit, which remember is the right most Qubit, then we'll get a zero or a one

549
59:18.270 --> 59:22.800
depending on which state we started with.

550
59:22.800 --> 59:30.180
Alternatively, we can consider
a projective measurement with outcomes zero to one
defined as you see right here.

551
59:30.180 --> 59:33.780
in this case, the measurement
actually only depends on Psi.

552
59:33.780 --> 59:38.460
This measurement perfectly
discriminates Psi from any state that's orthogonal to Psi.

553
59:38.460 --> 59:46.380
If we measure Psi with respect to this projective measurement, then we'll get the outcome
zero with probability one as these equations review.

554
59:46.380 --> 59:52.380
And for any state Phi
that's orthogonal to Psi, we'll get the outcome
one with probability one.

555
59:52.380 --> 59:59.580
I won't go through the
details of these calculations, but if you're interested, I encourage you to go through
the details on your own.

556
59:59.580 --> 60:06.570
And that is the end of lesson three. We covered a lot of
material in this lesson, including quantum circuits,

557
60:06.570 --> 60:14.100
inner products and orthonormality, projections and projective measurements, the fact that global phases don't matter,

558
60:14.100 --> 60:22.410
the no-cloning theorem, and the fact that non-orthogonal states can't be perfectly discriminated while orthogonal states can.

559
60:22.410 --> 60:29.010
I hope you'll join me for
the fourth lesson soon, which is the last lesson in
the first unit of the series.

560
60:29.010 --> 60:36.390
In the fourth lesson, we'll talk about three
very important examples, teleportation, superdense coding,

561
60:36.390 --> 60:42.420
and the CHSH inequality or CHSH game as it's sometimes described.

562
60:42.420 --> 60:43.413
Goodbye until then,
